recordings.rmk:
Invisible bird singing in a circle of trees and bushes, in prairie area, at a distance of about 100 m from the lake. Perhaps Acrocephalus palustris ? Thank you for your opinions.
Bernard
**********
Confirmation by Gérard Olivier and Ulf Elman

Two marsh warblers singing around 150 meters NE and NW of the recording place, respectively. The first singer you hear is the NE one. At 0:55 I turn the parabola 90 degrees left (e.g. towards the NW location). The voice that you hear after that is not as forceful as the first one. At 2:40 I start turning the parabola back towards NE, which you can verify because at 2:45 the NE singer comes in from the right. Telinga Pro 5W with Stereo DAT mic, some noise filtering. 

I have earlier recorded marsh warblers many times at the exact NE and NW singing places. The NW place is a dense big shrub while NE is a small shrub where the bird cannot hide. Later the same night only the NE singer was heard. My interpretation is that this is a couple that migrate together and that the NW singer is the female, possibly at the nesting place.

From XC481967 it seems that the marsh warblers arrived the same afternoon. I think that the singer on that recording is the NE one, i.e. the suggested male.

Also compare https://vimeo.com/343480491, recorded next morning. It shows very clearly that there are two different singing marsh warblers.

Contributed for the female bird song project: femalebirdsong.org.

recordings.rmk:
Mainly a long Marsh Warbler song, though a Common Blackbird and a Garden Warbler intervene. But there are a lot of recognizable imitations: Common Chaffinch (00:05, 11:00), Eurasian Blue Tit (00:12, 05:07), Eurasian Nuthatch (00:55, 08:18), Great Tit (01:10, 0:1:31, 05:31 - Frühlingsläuten, 08:53, 10:03, 10:16), Common Redstart (01:16), Black Redstart (2:30), Barn Swallow (01:37, 07:38-07:50, even song imit.), Common Blackbird (01:56, 02:07 - auch Luftalarm, 04:53, 05:32 ), Common Buzzard (02:18, 02:40), European Goldfinch (04:28, 08:37), Common Starling (07:35), European Greenfinch (09:41). In 07:33 he imitates a special whistle, the same which I heard years before from a Song Thrush in Southern Tyrol - compareXC428866 and XC428868  - may be a herdsman whistle (?)
From 02:23 a Common Blackbird begins to intervene, with a wonderful warbling motive, from 03:39 a GardenWarbler. In 07:00 the Blackbird flies on the post against that I lean, frighthens and calls alarm until 11:57, when he begins singing again.

One individual to the left, another to the right. The left one from time to time influences the right one, initiating antiphonal song with the left bird leading and the right bird following. Such untiphonal song occurs 03:41.7 with mimicry of Nightinggale (Luscinia luscinia), 00:07.9 with mimicry of Blue tits, 03:14.6 with mimicry of Greenfinch (Chloris choris) and 01:48.3 with mimicry of an unidentified probably African bird.

recordings.loc: Vřesová, Sokolov District, Karlovy Vary Region
recordings.rmk:
This is either a Blyth's reed warbler (Acrocephalus dumetorum), or a Marsh warbler (Acrocephalus palustris), or a hybrid. Note that there is only one confirmed case of Blyth's in the Czech republic. Attempts to catch the bird have failed and the bird seems to be gone now. Comments on the song
are very welcome. (Typical for Blyth's? Intermediate between both species? Or just somewhat unusual Marsh warbler?)

Update: thanks to reactions on the forum, I now feel confident this is a sleepy Marsh warbler.
The "sleepy" slow speed of the song is reminiscent of Blyth's but the sounds themselves point to Marsh warbler and in other recordings of the same individual (in particular, XC326311) it sounds more like a normal Marsh warbler.

recordings.rmk: Blyth´s Reed Warbler or a slow Marsh Warbler??? Sang constantly from about 1½ meters height in a willow bush in a fertile Phragmites marsh from I arrived at 23:20 24/5 till I left at 00:40 25/5. Audible for about 2-300 meters and thus seemed louder than the normal marsh warblers also present in the same marsh. The song quality also seemed slower and with less squeeks and harsh sounds than I usually hear from marsh warblers. From a distance the sound first reminded me of nightingale - perhaps this was mimicked before I came close and made the recording? The mp3 file was made as a rip from an AVI file taken by a Canon powershot camera. no other alterations.
